The entirety of Disneywars is a combination of "I have an idea and a message and it's going to fit into this movie!" and "Wouldn't it be cool if?!" storytelling.

The actually good parts are incidental and accidental.

@Brejan 
*"To be fair, Lucas didn't have that much of a plan either, or at least not one that resembled  the finished product."*
This is a great point I think far too many old school Star Wars fans fail to acknowledge. Because of the OT's success, and because Lucas has always been a revisionist (damn near a liar) about his work on the OT, way too many people seem to think Lucas had a much more detailed plan than he actually did. As I said, Lucas is a revisionist; he continually says things like, "This is what I always intended / wanted," when it's relatively easy to go back and find him stating the exact opposite between 1977 and 1983. It's true that he put together a *VERY* rough outline of the entire Saga fairly early on, then decided to make the second half of it first. But that's about it. Since 1981, he's regularly claimed that Vader was *ALWAYS* intended to be Luke's father, but the actual drafts and versions of the story treatments and screenplays _he wrote_ directly contradict this idea. In fact, in many of the early drafts, the character that became Luke Skywalker was either the father himself, or his father was in the story as a Jedi. It wasn't until part way through drafting the script for _The Empire Strikes Back_ that he finally decided Vader was definitely Luke's father. The same is true about Luke and Leia being twins; Lucas claims that was always the plan, but there's evidence _in his own writing_ that he didn't actually finalize that decision until he had started working on _Return of the Jedi._ Even Yoda's line when Luke leaves Dagobah in Empire, "No. There is another," wasn't definitively referring to Leia when it was filmed.

